 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · Rules of Surds",
   "html": "<p>A <b>surd</b> is an irrational root such as $\\sqrt 2$, $\\sqrt 3$, $\\sqrt[3]{5}$.</p>$$\\sqrt a \\cdot \\sqrt b = \\sqrt{ab},\\qquad \\sqrt{\\dfrac{a}{b}} = \\dfrac{\\sqrt a}{\\sqrt b},\\qquad k\\sqrt a + m\\sqrt a = (k+m)\\sqrt a$$<p>Simplify by extracting perfect squares: $\\sqrt{50} = \\sqrt{25\\cdot 2} = 5\\sqrt 2$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Simplify $\\sqrt{72}$.",
     "a": "$\\sqrt{72} = \\sqrt{36\\cdot 2} = 6\\sqrt 2$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Rationalizing Denominators",
   "html": "<p>Multiply numerator and denominator by the surd (or its conjugate) to remove the surd from the denominator.</p>$$\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt a} \\cdot \\dfrac{\\sqrt a}{\\sqrt a} = \\dfrac{\\sqrt a}{a},\\qquad \\dfrac{1}{a+\\sqrt b}\\cdot \\dfrac{a-\\sqrt b}{a-\\sqrt b} = \\dfrac{a-\\sqrt b}{a^2-b}$$",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Rationalize $\\dfrac{3}{\\sqrt 2}$.",
     "a": "$\\dfrac{3}{\\sqrt 2}\\cdot\\dfrac{\\sqrt 2}{\\sqrt 2} = \\dfrac{3\\sqrt 2}{2}$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Conjugate Surds",
   "html": "<p>The <b>conjugate</b> of $a+\\sqrt b$ is $a-\\sqrt b$. Their product $(a+\\sqrt b)(a-\\sqrt b) = a^2 - b$ is rational.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Rationalize $\\dfrac{1}{2+\\sqrt 3}$.",
     "a": "Multiply by $\\tfrac{2-\\sqrt 3}{2-\\sqrt 3}$: $\\dfrac{2-\\sqrt 3}{4-3} = 2-\\sqrt 3$."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
